title: For Sale:  Dan Wesson Model 22 Target Revolver .22LR
postcontent: I have for sale a Dan Wesson Model 22 Target six shot .22 LR revolver, in very good condition.  This is one of the the more desirable Monson, Massachusetts manufactured revolvers.  It has a six inch barrel, with vent rib & heavy underlug barrel shroud, and a Hogue rubber Monogrip.  Back in the day, many competitors preferred these over the Smith & Wesson 17, for the following reasons:  The barrels & shrouds could be easily changed for ones of different lengths and styles, the barrel being tensioned at both ends was considered to be more accurate due to harmonics, the barrel to cylinder gap could be set to user preference, front sight could be easily changed for ones of differnent colors, the double action trigger pull was shorter (faster lock time), fewer internal parts & easier to disassemble internals without special tools, trigger overtravel adjustment screw was standard, stronger front cylinder crane lock-up.  Barrels, barrel shrouds, and other parts are still readily available.My price is $675, with a trade value of $725.  I'd rather sell than trade, but will consider trading for 9mm CZ pistols, 9mm Browning Hi Power pistols with Hard Chrome or Nickle finish, or "Tactical" (not Hunting) type firearms.  Meeting location will be in N. The .357 Magnum is a revolver cartridge created by Elmer Keith, Phillip Sharpe, Winchester, and the firearms manufacturer Smith and Wesson, based upon Smith and Wesson's earlier .38 Special cartridge. The .357 Magnum was developed over a period of time in the early to mid-1930s in a direct response to Colt's .38 Super Automatic. At the time, the .38 Super was the only pistol cartridge capable of defeating automobile cover and the early body armor that was just beginning to emerge in the post-World War I "Gangster Era".
